The Adapter Pattern is what you reach for when two pieces of code should work together but
don’t because their interfaces don’t match. Instead of rewriting either side, you build a small
translator in between.

Core Idea
Target interface → what your app expects
Adaptee → existing class with a different interface
Adapter → converts one into the other


Step 1. Define the Target Interface
interface PaymentProcessor {
    public function pay($amount);
}

Step 2. Existing Class (Adaptee)
class StripeAPI {
    public function makePayment($amountInCents) {
        echo "Paid {$amountInCents} cents using Stripe\n";
    }
}

Problem:
Method name is different
Amount format is different

Step 3. Create the Adapter => This is the bridge

class StripeAdapter implements PaymentProcessor {
    private $stripe;

    public function __construct(StripeAPI $stripe) {
        $this->stripe = $stripe;
    }

    public function pay($amount) {
        // Convert dollars to cents
        $amountInCents = $amount * 100;

        // Call the adaptee method
        $this->stripe->makePayment($amountInCents);
    }
}


Step 4. Use It Like Nothing Happened
$stripe = new StripeAPI();

$payment = new StripeAdapter($stripe);
$payment->pay(50);



